ocial action. In this collection of articles, Podgórecki's work is a linchpin for debate among social policy practitioners and theorists from Europe and North America. Their studies span a wide spectrum: Nixon and the Watergate scandal, Jaruzelski's Martial Law in Poland, Soviet myth-building, the Canadian anti-smoking campaign, earthquake planning, native land claims, "infoglut," and self-fulfilling prophecy. Yet these diverse analyses clearly support and enhance one another along carefully defined themes of guided social action. Social Engineering is an important addition to the shelves of public policy libraries and will be as illuminating to governments, corporations, policy consultants and special interest groups as it is to theorists.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aSocial engineering. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aAlexander, John, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aAlexander, Jon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBenveniste, Guy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCove, John J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCsaba, Kathleen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHay, Robert Philip B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHenshel, Richard L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJabtonński, Adam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJackson, Ray, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKojder, Andrzej, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKubin, Jerzy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLewarne, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relat